Suppose our model learns these coefficients:
\begin{align*} \beta_0 &= 8 \quad \text{(intercept)} \\ \beta_{\text{DTI}} &= 0.05 \quad \text{(debt-to-income ratio, in \%)} \\ \beta_{\text{FICO}} &= -0.015 \quad \text{(credit score)} \end{align*}

Low-risk borrower: DTI = 25% and FICO = 750
\begin{align*} \text{Linear part} &= 8 + 0.05 \times 25 + (-0.015) \times 750 = 8 + 1.25 - 11.25 = -2.0 \end{align*}
\[ P(\text{default}) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-(-2.0)}} = \frac{1}{1 + e^{2}} \approx \mathbf{0.12} \quad \text{(12\%)} \]

High-risk borrower: DTI = 45% and FICO = 620
\begin{align*} \text{Linear part} &= 8 + 0.05 \times 45 + (-0.015) \times 620 = 8 + 2.25 - 9.30 = 0.95 \end{align*}
\[ P(\text{default}) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-0.95}} \approx \mathbf{0.72} \quad \text{(72\%)} \]

Suppose our logistic regression model learns these coefficients for predicting loan default:
\begin{align*} \beta_0 &= 8 \quad \text{(intercept)} \\ \beta_{\text{DTI}} &= 0.05 \quad \text{(debt-to-income ratio, in \%)} \\ \beta_{\text{FICO}} &= -0.015 \quad \text{(credit score)} \end{align*}

For a low-risk borrower with DTI = 25% and FICO = 750:
\begin{align*} \text{Linear combination} &= 8 + 0.05 \times 25 + (-0.015) \times 750 = 8 + 1.25 - 11.25 = -2.0 \\ P(\text{default}) &= \frac{1}{1 + e^{-(-2.0)}} = \frac{1}{1 + e^{2}} \approx 0.12 \end{align*}

For a high-risk borrower with DTI = 45% and FICO = 620:
\begin{align*} \text{Linear combination} &= 8 + 0.05 \times 45 + (-0.015) \times 620 = 8 + 2.25 - 9.30 = 0.95 \\ P(\text{default}) &= \frac{1}{1 + e^{-0.95}} \approx 0.72 \end{align*}

The model assigns a 12% default probability to the good borrower and 72% to the risky one.
